
| Order | Paper Title                                                                                              | Main Topic                         | Why Read It at This Stage?                                                                                                 |
| ----: | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
|     1 | **Stability and Control of a Quadrocopter Despite the Complete Loss of One, Two, or Three Propellers**   | Fundamental Fault-Tolerant Control | Introduces the basic concept of fault-tolerant flight with relatively simple control strategies. Excellent starting point. |
|     2 | **Uniform Passive Fault-Tolerant Control for a Quadcopter Subject to One, Two, or Three Rotor Failures** | Passive Fault-Tolerant Control     | Extends the classical FTC framework using disturbance estimation and dynamic control allocation.                           |
|     3 | **Nonlinear MPC for Quadrotor Fault-Tolerant Control**                                                   | Model Predictive Control           | Read after learning MPC. Demonstrates how nonlinear optimization is applied to quadrotor control.                          |
|     4 | **Learning-Based Passive Fault-Tolerant Control for Quadrotor (Selector-Controller Network)**            | Reinforcement Learning + FTC       | Requires understanding of both control theory and introductory reinforcement learning.                                     |
|     5 | **MorphoCopter: Design, Modeling, and Control of a New Transformable Quad-Bi Copter**                    | Morphing UAV                       | Introduces morphing aerial vehicles and adaptive control concepts.                                                         |
|     6 | **Nezha-FX: A Morphing HAUV Designed Based on Balanced Cross-Domain Performance Optimization**           | Hybrid Aerial-Underwater Robot     | Expands morphing concepts to cross-domain robotics and multi-objective design optimization.                                |
|     7 | **ModQuad: The Flying Modular Structure that Self-Assembles in Midair**                                  | Modular Aerial Robotics            | Introduces modular aerial robots and mid-air docking mechanisms.                                                           |
|     8 | **BEATLE—Self-Reconfigurable Aerial Robot: Design, Control and Experimental Validation**                 | Modular Self-Reconfiguration       | Presents improved docking mechanisms and coordinated flight of connected aerial modules.                                   |
|     9 | **Modular Aerial Robotic Systems (MARS): Robust Self-Reconstruction Algorithm**                          | Modular Robotics                   | Introduces controllability-aware self-reconfiguration algorithms.                                                          |
|    10 | **TransforMARS: A General Fault-Tolerant Reconfiguration Framework**                                     | Advanced Modular Robotics          | Generalizes MARS to arbitrary structures and multiple rotor/unit failures.                                                 |
|    11 | **Resilient Odometry via Hierarchical Adaptation (Super Odometry)**                                      | Sensor Fusion & State Estimation   | Best studied after Kalman filtering and state estimation fundamentals.                                                     |
|    12 | **Robot Metabolism: Toward Machines That Can Grow by Consuming Other Machines**                          | Robot Morphology & Adaptation      | A visionary paper discussing long-term physical adaptation and self-growth of modular robots.                              |
|    13 | **Laser-assisted Failure Recovery for Dielectric Elastomer Actuators in Aerial Robots**                  | Soft Robotics                      | Specialized work on self-repairing soft actuators; less directly related to your current control-focused roadmap.          |

